DEMO TRANSCRIPT (PDF)

ShopSphere Fullstack – End-to-End Demo Transcript

1) Project overview
Hi everyone. Today I’m demonstrating ShopSphere, a full-stack ecommerce application.
The UI is built with React + Vite + Tailwind, and the backend is built with Express.
Data persistence in this project uses JSON-based storage, so the app runs without setting up MongoDB.

2) Start the application
First, I’ll start the backend server.
I run the server locally, and it exposes REST APIs under /api.
Next, I start the frontend development server.
Once both are running, the ecommerce UI loads in the browser.

3) Browse products
Now I’ll show product browsing.
On the Home page, I can view categories and product cards.
Clicking a product opens the product details page.
This pulls product data from the backend /api/products route.

4) Search and filter (quick demo)
Next, I’ll demonstrate search and filter.
I type into the search bar to find relevant products.
Then I apply a category filter to narrow down results.
The product list updates based on the frontend filtering logic using the loaded catalog.

5) Add items to cart (requires login)
Now I’ll add a product to the cart.
If I’m not logged in, the app prevents adding to the cart and prompts me to log in.
So I’ll log in first.

6) Authentication (Login)
On the Login page, I enter email and password.
After successful login, the app stores the auth token in localStorage.
The navigation updates to show authenticated options.

7) Add to cart
Back to the catalog, I add an item to the cart.
The frontend calls POST /api/cart with the productId and quantity.
The cart state updates immediately in the UI.

8) View cart and proceed to checkout
Now I open the Cart page.
I can review the selected products and quantities.
The cart totals are calculated from line items.
Next, I click “Proceed to Checkout”.

9) Checkout
On the Checkout page, the form is prefilled using the logged-in user data.
I enter shipping details such as address, city, and postal code.
Then I click “Place Order”.
The frontend sends the order payload to POST /api/orders.
On the backend, the order is created with status = “Placed”, and the user’s cart is cleared.
After success, the user is redirected to the Orders page.

10) Order history (Orders page)
Now I’m on the Order History page.
This page fetches orders from GET /api/orders, filtered by the authenticated user.
Each order is displayed via an OrderCard component.
I can see the order id, customer details, status, created date, and items with totals.

11) Cancel order (status-based action)
Next, I demonstrate order cancellation.
On an order with status “Placed”, the “Cancel Order” button is available.
Clicking it opens a cancellation modal.
I enter a cancellation reason, confirm, and the app calls PATCH /api/orders/:orderId/cancel.
On the backend, the API validates ownership and ensures the order is currently “Placed”.
Then it updates the status to “Cancelled” and stores the cancellation reason.
The UI reflects the updated status after the response.

12) Summary / closing
That concludes the demo.
ShopSphere shows end-to-end ecommerce flows:
- browse products
- search/filter
- authenticated cart and checkout
- create orders and view order history
- cancel orders with validation

Thanks for watching.
